Arsenal, Inc., the premier American importer and manufacturer of Kalashnikov-pattern rifles and pistols, is proud to offer to the American enthusiast the Bulgarian-made SAM7K Pistol. Arsenal’s Exclusive Milled And Forged Receiver
Each SAM7K receiver is milled from a hot-die hammer forged receiver blank by the Arsenal Co. of Bulgaria. title: For Sale:  1911 45acp
postcontent:
Taurus PT1911 

Includes two 8 round magazines, box and manual Does show some holster wear, no damage to pistol. excerpt from Gunblast.com As stated above, all ammo functioned perfectly with both magazines provided with the pistol. The Taurus PT1911 is an all-steel, five inch barreled 1911, just as John Browning intended his .45 caliber pistol to be. After almost one hundred years, the 1911 .45 automatic is still the standard to which all fighting pistols are compared. Even with all of the designs introduced in the past few decades, the 1911 is still the choice of professionals who have to carry a handgun into a fight. The Taurus is a superb weapon, right out of the box. The only change that I would make if this were my personal weapon would be to add a set of night sights for use in very low light situations. Another good alternative would be Crimson Trace Lasergrips. The Heinie sights are very good, however, and offer a good sight picture, but I just prefer tritium inserts. The PT1911 is a heck of a good value in a quality 1911 pistol. It is made from forged steel, has a very good blued finish, and a long list of upgraded parts that would cost extra on most pistols in its price range. I usually don’t list retail prices in my articles, as the articles stay up on Gunblast for years, but this PT1911 sells for about the same price as a basic 1911 did thirty years ago. The suggested retail price on this gun, as of July 2006, is only $599 US. That is a real bargain for a 1911 with this many features, with this good of a trigger pull, that is this accurate. It is a high quality fighting pistol, and I highly recommend this Taurus PT1911.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Mosin Nagant Scout Rifle
postcontent: This rifle was originally a Russian 91/30. But then I got bored. I stripped and refinished the stock and all of the metal. I cut down the barrel (well within the legal limits) and re crowned it. All of the metal has been coated with Brownells Aluma Hyde II. It is a very tough finish. I added the butt pad as well. I am not a gunsmith and the rifle was built by the Soviets, so this is not some fancy piece of art. This is not an $800 sporterized Mauser project. This is a Scout Rifle/Brush Gun. Still, it turned out really well and shoots straight. I fired 20+ rounds through it since completing the project and carried it hunting. This rifle is very light and very short, so a word to the wise, don't buy it if you don't like recoil or if you think 12 inch flames coming out of the barrel is a bad thing. Comes with 100+ rounds of ammunition, 20 of which are soft points for hunting and the red dot.

title: For Sale:  1970 RUGER OLD MODEL SUPER BLACKHAWK RARE "D" PREFIX SERIAL WITH HOLSTER
postcontent: This is for the revolver lovers out there. For sale or possible trade is a very rare 1970 Ruger Super Blackhawk .44mag. What makes it very rare is the fact that it has the "D" serial Prefix. There were roughly only 800 "D" prefix Supers made. The "D" stands for Duplicate. This means somewhere out there there is a different caliber Ruger with the same serial minus the "D". Also a great feature of the gun is that it has not been converted to the transfer bar setup and it is a super high polish bluing on the gun. I would rate the bluing at 95% with only slight holster wear on the tip of the barrel, light hand wear on the back strap, and a light scratch here or there. For a 44 year old pistol, it is very nice. Someone has replaced the grips, so from a collector standpoint, they need to be replaced with a factory set. The rubber houge grips do have a bit of the rubber chipped out on one side. On another bright note, it surprisingly does not look to have been shot much, and the action is smooth as silk. The trigger pull is insanely crisp and light and the cylinder is tight. Here is a link that explains many of the odd features of this piece: http://www.gunblast.com/Hamm_SuperBlackhawk1.htm . I will sell the pistol for $700 cash or listen to trade offers. I really dont have anything in particular in mind on a trade. Trade plus cash on your side or even trades only please. I am located in Cleveland, TN. Text or call REDACTED if interested. Text me trades offers with pics if possible. The pictures really dont do it justice. The nice leather Cross Draw holster is included, and it can be worn on the side as well. Thanks-Dave

title: For Sale:  WALTHER PP MANURHIN 7.65, w/box & mags, not PPK, PPK/S
postcontent:
I have a French made (Walther licensed) PP chambered in .32 auto (7.65 Browning). In the immediate aftermath of WWII, Walther was forced to move manufacturing out of Germany. This gun was made under license by "Manufacture de Machines Du Haut-Rhin" or MANURHIN starting in the '50s. It has matching serial numbers (slide, frame, magazine) and St. Etienne proof marks. There is a small Interarms import stamp on the frame. Gun shows some holster wear but is in otherwise good condition, bore is bright and grips are in great shape. also comes with box, brass cleaning rod and a second magazine. shipping is $25

WALTHER'S ORIGINAL FACTORY WAS LOCATED IN ZELLA-MEHLIS IN THE STATE (LAND) OF THURINGIA, IN PRESENT-DAY EASTERN GERMANY. AS THAT PART OF GERMANY WAS OCCUPIED BY THE SOVIET UNION FOLLOWING WORLD WAR II, WALTHER WAS FORCED TO FLEE TO WEST GERMANY, WHERE THEY ESTABLISHED A NEW FACTORY IN ULM. HOWEVER, FOR SEVERAL YEARS FOLLOWING THE WAR, THE ALLIED POWERS FORBADE ANY MANUFACTURE OF WEAPONS IN GERMANY. AS A RESULT, IN 1952, WALTHER LICENSED PRODUCTION OF THE PP SERIES PISTOLS TO A FRENCH COMPANY, MANUFACTURE DE MACHINES DU HAUT-RHIN, ALSO KNOWN AS MANURHIN. THE FRENCH COMPANY CONTINUED TO MANUFACTURE THE PP SERIES UNTIL 1986. IN FACT, ALL POSTWAR EUROPEAN-MADE PP SERIES PISTOLS MANUFACTURED UNTIL 1986 WERE MANUFACTURED BY MANURHIN.

I am selling this rifle to partially fund the purchase of a SCAR 17.  So the only trade that I will even entertain is for a black SCAR 17 where I will throw in extra Cash.

There are a few minor scratches and dings in the finish of the rifle from light use but everything is very minor and hardly noticeable
